dataset.title: Results, Code and Data for Quantitative Assessment of Stabilizing or Destabilizing Effect of Fjord Geometry on Greenland Tidewater Glaciers 1985-2020

abstract.para: To download and unzip this dataset, manually download the file a00_download_arcticdata.py, and then run using Python3:
NOTE: You may have to authenticate and set the TOKEN environment variable, see the "Authentication" section of:

This study systematically examines the stress state of Greenland tidewater glaciers based on available surface velocities, terminus positions, ice thickness and bed elevations. The von Mises Calving Law is used to assess the contributions of fjord geometry to a glacier’s stability, or lack thereof. If a glacier’s expected calving rate increases upon terminus retreat after taking into account the empirical ocean heating relationship of, then fjord geometry contributes to instability; whereas a decrease signals a stabilizing fjord contribution.

This principle is used to systematically evaluate 44 Greenland tidewater glaciers. Of those glaciers, 13 were found to have fjord geometry that currently contributes to instability; 7 with stabilizing geometry; and 24 that lacked statistical significance. Although the methodology as it currently stands is able to provide insight on a variety of already-retreating glaciers, it is only able to analyze terminus positions that have already been realized in the past. Therefore, it is unable to provide insight on historically stable glaciers, or on future terminus positions for which fjord geometry might change from stabilizing to destabilizing or vice versa. Future studies involving dynamic ice models could use the methodology presented here to address those questions.
Full per-glaciers results are included. Python code to download external datasets, process / plot results and repeat this study is included, along with all datasets generated by this study.

section.title: Ethical Research Practices
section.para: Data included in this dataset were generated by hand and from models, based on available datasets from pre-existing studies by third parties.

description.para: Procedures are outlined in the Python code. A series of Python scripts are included: a01, a02, ..., b01, b02, ... They are to be run in order to re-generate plots and analyses of this study. Regeneration of the von Mises stress (sigma) fields is possible using the code in this dataset, but requires additional linkage to PISM, the Parallel Ice Sheet Model.
Greenland Ice Sheet, 1x/yr. Tidewater glaciers were chosen based on availability of data from previous studies cited.

samplingDescription.para: Annual ITS-LIVE surface velocity dataset (cited) is used. Sigma is calculated based on these surface velocities using PISM (Parallel Ice Model). For each glacier, all available sigma fields are integrated along all available termin to produce the raw data. Further steps analyze, process and plot the results.

dataTable.entityDescription: The “master table” of the study, including input datasets and results. The study relied on data from multiple previous studies, and this table provides the key to corresponding glaciers between studies. For example, the terminus data provided by Wood et al (2021) in the file AP Bernstorff Data.nc corresponds to the glacier called A.P. Bernstorf Gl. or glacier number 62 in the Wood et al (2021) supplement spreadsheet. It is also the same as the glacier GGN0089 in Bjørk, Kruse, Michaelsen (2015) and Glacier number 190 of NSIDC Dataset 642. Each dataset is encoded as a column name prefix

attribute.attributeDefinition: Alphabetic name of each glacier, used in filenames of terminus positions provided with the Wood et al, 2021 study. For example, the file Ussing Braeer Data.nc contains data for the glacier with w21t_Glacier == 'Ussing Braeer Data'. Most generally, this is the name assigned to the glacier by the Wood et al, 2021 study.
Greenlandic name of glacier
Numeric ID assigned to each glacier in the Wood et al, 2021 study, and used in some parts of the dataset.
Single longitude point representing the terminus, based on an average of the terminus locations over time, as provided by the Wood et al, 2021 study.
Single latitude point representing the terminus, based on an average of the terminus locations over time, as provided by the Wood et al, 2021 study.

A combination of two fields from the data provided with the Wood et al, 2021 study, together, uniquely identify each glacier. Additional columns from [w21] may be obtained by joining with original data.
Numeric identifier for each point inside the source shapefile of hand drawn fjords (fjord_outlines.zip). (Points are matched to glaciers through spatial analysis, not matching IDs).
The identifier for each grid used in the MEaSUREs Greenland Ice Velocity dataset. For example, W71.65N describes the grid found on the West coast of Greenland at 71.65 degrees North.
Numeric identifier for each point inside the source shapefile of upstream points (upstream_points.zip). (Points are matched to glaciers through spatial analysis, not matching IDs).
Column is blank and unused.
Location of the upstream point (from upstream_points.zip)
Location of the upstream point (from upstream_points.zip)
Alphanumeric ID assigned to each glacier by the source paper. Additional columns from [bkm15] may be obtained by joining with original data.
Alphabetic name of each glacier, used in filenames of the CALFIN dataset.
The GlacierID column found inside the CALFIN dataset shapefile(s)
ID used to identify glaciers in NSIDC dataset #642: MEaSUREs Annual Greenland Outlet Glacier Terminus Positions from SAR Mosaics, Version 2 (NSIDC-0642) https://nsidc.org/data/nsidc-0642/versions/2
The bjorkid from the glaciers.mat file provided with the Slater, 2019 paper. Should correspond to the column bkm15_id described above.
The column called rignotid from the glaciers.mat file provided with the Slater, 2019 paper. Additional columns from [sl19] may be obtained by joining with original data.
Same as sl19_rignotid.
Regression between terminus positions of [sl19] vs up-areas derived from data in [w21t], as described in this study, slope

Regression between terminus positions of [sl19] vs up-areas derived from data in [w21t], as described in this study, standard error
Repeat of the regressions from [sl19], as described in this study.

dataTable.entityDescription: Relationship between w21 (Wood 2021) and sl19 dataset, as determined by finding pairs (w,s) in which w ∈ w21, s ∈ sl19 and the terminus as reported in the datasets of w and b are close together. otherEntity.entityDescription:
Script auto-downloads all files in this dataset, and places them in a nested directory structure. Requires Python version 3. Steps to download are:
(1) Manually download the file a00_download_arcticdata.py
(2) Run: python a00-download_arcticdata.py ~/greenland_calving 3
This will download sections 1-3 of the dataset into the directory ~/greenland_calving. Sections are (1): results, (2) original data from this study, (3) Python code to reproduce results, and (4) Gridded sigma files. Section 4 is largest and can be skipped by most users.
